For {= resource =}+ core human PDAC, pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma, or clearly pancreas-cancer public cohort resources, data records, atlas/accession series, or patient/specimen resource programs with multi-omics or multimodal public metadata, supply at least {= url =} public source-record URLs per resource. Each URL should be a distinct direct source record for that resource, not merely a parameterized text/full/view/export form of the same page, and should support a factual metadata entry: resource short and canonical names, resource type, disease-scope classification, source family/name, observed source fact, source date if visible, checked date, modality and count claims, clinical-annotation status, access state, relationship to the submitted resource, confidence, and missing or conflict flags.

The useful entries are metadata-only. They can include public source records for open files, open metadata with controlled data, application or DUA access, unavailable or retired records, and missing or conflicting metadata states. Do not submit clinical-only registries, early-detection cohorts without a public omics/multimodal data record, administrative datasets, model-only resources, broad mixed-site programs, retired portal stubs, or other boundary/exclusion cases as root resources. Those boundary cases are useful only as explicitly sourced cautions, related-source notes, or negative evidence when they explain why a tempting record should not be counted. Do not rank resources, recommend them for modeling or treatment decisions, infer clinical suitability, require raw-data downloads, or imply a way around controlled-access systems.

`resource` ought to name one underlying core cohort, program cohort, accession series, atlas project, or patient/specimen data resource. Mirror portals, analysis views, aggregate indexes, and repository pages for the same underlying cohort belong under the same `resource` through separate URLs; different cohorts under the same umbrella program should stay separate. Do not submit repeated accession labels, publication titles, portal names, API/text/full/export views, or analysis mirrors as new resources when they identify the same underlying GEO/SRA/EGA/CPTAC/TCGA/cBioPortal/LinkedOmics/OmicsDI/GDC/PRIDE/ProteomeXchange record family.

Requirements:
- The page must identify the submitted resource or source record directly enough to ground the resource name, source family, source name, direct identifier, and observed source fact.
- Each submitted URL for the same resource must be a distinct source record or source-record family. Alternate GEO text/full views, API/export parameter variants, equivalent portal renderings, mirror pages, and repeated accession views of the same source record do not count as separate corroborating URLs. Prefer genuinely distinct record families where available, such as an accession/registry page plus a publication, OmicsDI, cBioPortal, LinkedOmics, GDC, PRIDE/ProteomeXchange, EGA, or other official/aggregate record that independently identifies the same resource relationship.
- The page must support the submitted disease-scope classification: PDAC-specific, PAAD-or-pancreas-cancer, mixed pancreas with a sourced pancreas-cancer subset, or human patient/specimen atlas. A pancreas primary-site label is not automatically PDAC-specific, and a boundary/exclusion label does not make an otherwise invalid root resource count.
- The page must support the submitted data-domain status: a core entry needs at least one molecular omics modality plus another omics, imaging/pathology, spatial, single-cell, clinical, or biospecimen domain. Clinical-only, biospecimen-only, administrative, model-only, or merely broad pancreas primary-site records do not satisfy the root resource bar without a public multi-omics or multimodal patient/specimen data record.
- The page must support the submitted clinical-annotation status for at least one relevant facet, such as clinical metadata, survival or outcome, treatment exposure, response or resistance, subtype or molecular class, early detection, longitudinal follow-up, or biospecimen availability. Explicit, partial, absent, conflicting, and unclear states are all acceptable when the source record supports that status.
- The page must support the submitted access state, distinguishing public metadata from open downloadable files, controlled-access data, application or DUA routes, consortium/trial-only availability, unavailable or retired records, and unclear access information.
- Each source record must state its relationship to the submitted resource. Primary/official source records can say they are the primary official record; non-primary, mirror, analysis-portal, aggregate, publication, API, or related-program URLs must state whether they are the same cohort, mirror or analysis view, same program, related but not the same subjects, plausible but unproven, conflicting, missing, or count-disagreeing evidence. The page must support the asserted relationship and any missing/conflict/count-disagreement notes.
